climbs.name: Tick on a Tick on a Tater

content.description: Start on a soft corner arete with good holds throughout. Medium to large footholds make for secure climbing. Top out is slightly precarious because the large rock with a great hold at the top sounds hollow, However I yanked on it really hard and it felt completely solid.
content.protection: Pads. Can be done without pads but a rough fall.
content.location: About 20 feet to the right of "The Good Book". Follow the cliff band to the right of the first major overlook, in a grassy patch, with lots of downed trees and shrubs.

content.description: Star with left hand in a sharp and shallow crack and right hand around a bulged corner. Work your way through wide moves and really wide feet until you switch to a strange layback sort of move, and get to a really nice Shark fin with awesome juggy holds.
content.location: Directly in between "The Good Book" and "Tick on a Tick on a Tater". Obvious shark fin about 10 feet up

content.description: This starts to the right of End of the Line on a small crimps and in the crack out right. You move up into a sidepulling crimp, then to one more above and bomb for the garbage sloper top. Stick this then top it out.
content.location: This route is just to the right of end of the line.

content.description: Start in a small roof and move straight up through some side pulls and shallow ledges.
Starts at a leaning crack in a corner. Move up to the roof hand crack and work your way around to the top.
content.location: To the right of “Double Decker”. On the corner of the cliff.

content.description: The first established boulder at this overlook. Easy open book corner. Start low in the corner and work your way up simple and fun moves with good holds throughout. Hardest part is finding some of the better holds as they are hidden. Pretty easy top out too.
content.protection: Pads. Easy enough to do without pads but not a fun fall.
content.location: This can be found at the first overlook coming from "lower parking lot" at the Grass Lake overlook trail, part of the Grand Lakes Reserve. Once to the overlook off trail in a grassy patch, go the right side and follow a small band of cliff that gets taller. This boulder is the first of several along this 12-15 foot cliff band, which is above a much taller cliff band 20 feet past that.

content.description: A deceptively easy looking route with fun and unique movement. Starting with the two crimps for either hand and moving up through gastons and other various moves, to get to the crux which is grabbing the final hold on the face. While bombing for it you have to carefully set your feet up to make the grab for the hold easier, this hold takes you to the top to some ok slopers and then jugs further right.
content.location: Follow the shorter band of cliffs above the major cliffs about to the end of where it seems safe to boulder with a good landing. Look for the large rail near the ground and the crimps a few feet above it.

content.description:
V1 (Red): Start left with a ledge at check height. High right leg with a rock over move.

 V2 (Yellow): Start right with a series of smaller broken ledges. Move to the right of the tree, and check out the second level after the initial climb
content.location: Just to the right of the pine tree half way up. 8/12 feet right of "Blade of Glory".

content.description: Start on a blank looking slab. Follow up a diagonal broken crack with sufficient holds. Make a final committing move to a higher ledge.
content.protection: pads. Watch for the death blade at the bottom
content.location: Start is just left of a pine tree half way up the cliff, also 8 feet left of "Double Decker".

content.description: Start below the pine trees. Work your way up through a soft open book into the branches
Start on the left face next to "The Good Book". Climb through a series of small ledges to the top.
This contains all the small cliffs on and around the major overlook. All of these are boulders
